President Trump IMpeachment Inquiry

Sunday 17 November

Gordon Sondland said to have worked closer with President Trump than previously thought.

The facts of the story:

  • On Saturday, a transcript from Tim Morrison, a top White House national security aide was released, in which he told impeachment investigators that Gordon Sondland was regularly in touch with President Donald Trump during the period of the infamous phone call with President Zelensky.
  • This is important because a key defence from the Trump administration is that the President had little involvement with the actions of his staff and that they were working without direct orders to do so.
  • Morrison, a Republican, also said that he did raise concerns with the call, although he did not think it was illegal, wanted it to be checked by the relevant officials.
  • He also stated that he was worried about relations between Sondland and President Trump, and tried to stay away from Trumps personal lawyer Rudy Giuliani.
  • Sondland and Morrison will testify in public this week.

Saturday 16 November

The facts of the story:

  • Ambassador Marie Yovanovitch became the third witness to testify in public impeachment hearings on Friday.
  • The former Ambassador to Ukraine was fired by President Trump in May, before the events that President Trump is being inquired about. Her deposition can be thought of as more of a character statement on the people involved in this, namely, President Trumps personal lawyer Rudy Giuliani and Ukraines prosecutor general (under the countrys previous administration) Yuri Lutsenko.
  • Lutensko spread rumours that Yovanovitch had a list of people she would not prosecute, this claim is unfounded and was later redacted.

  • Her deposition revolved around an apparent move by the Trump administration to push her out of the role. She was a career foreign diplomat and has served every US President since Reagan.
  • She was told to leave the role three days after President Zelensky was elected.
  • She spoke about shady channels of communication between the US and Ukranian administrations.
  • Yovanovitch: What I do wonder is why it was necessary to smear my reputation falsely.
  • In the infamous phone call with Zelensky, President Trump referred to her as bad news.

  • During her deposition, President Trump tweeted a public attack of her, when asked for a comment, she said the action was intimidating.
  • David Holmes had a closed-door deposition. Ambassador Bill Taylor testified on Wednesday that Holmes, his aide, overheard Gordon Sondland talk to President Trump on a phone call about how the investigations in Ukraine were going

Thursday 14 November

Beginning of Public hearings brings previously unheard of phone call.

The facts of the story:

  • Today was the first of the public impeachment inquiries. Today on the stand was Bill Taylor, the Acting US Ambassador to Ukraine and George Kent, who is the Deputy Assistant Secretary for European Affairs.
  • Both spoke privately to the House Intelligence Committee earlier last month, so no new information was expected.
  • Bill Taylor said that a staff member of his seen Gordon Sondland, the US Ambassador to the EU, speak to President Trump on the phone about investigations.
  • The same staffer told Taylor that Sondland said that President Trumps interest in Ukraine was primarily about the potential investigations of Biden.
  • George Kent said that he was told to keep his head down, on the topic of Ukraine.
  • President Trump said that he will now release an earlier call that he had with President Zelensky.

From around the web:

Saturday 9 November

National security European advisor testifies against president trump

The facts of the story:

  • The transcript of Lt Col Alexander Vindmans testimony is released, in which he says there was no doubt that President Trump expected a public investigation into Joe Bidens son, from the President of Ukraine. In return, President Trump would release the $400 million in military aid he has stalled.
  • Lt Col Vindman, who serves as the director for European affairs on the National Security Council, sat in on the phone call, which is now the subject of an impeachment inquiry.
  • At the time, Lt Col Vindman wrote a memo recommending that the military aid be released, although this was not acted upon.
